Quiz 1: Practice Quiz A

You are not logged in.

If you are a current student, please Log In for full access to the web site.
Note that this link will take you to an external site (https://shimmer.mit.edu) to authenticate, and then you will be redirected back to this page.

Please download the .zip file below, which contains all the files, test cases, etc., you need to complete the practice quiz using your own machine. When unzipped it will create its own directory with the quiz's files. The instructions follow below. You'll be editing quiz.py to add the code requested by the instructions.

Download: q1_practice_a.zip

How to take this practice quiz

Set aside a continuous block of time to attempt these problems. This is a past quiz so it can give you a feeling of what an actual quiz is like. During this quiz's semester, though, the quiz was closed book and closed Internet. As such, for the best practice experience, you should attend the quiz under those conditions.

Just like the labs, first run the tests on your computer before submitting online. Good luck!

Submission

When you have tested your code sufficiently on your own machine, you can submit your modified quiz.py below by clicking on "Choose File", then clicking the Submit button to send the file to the 6.009 server. In the real quiz, the server will queue your code and run the tests to score your quiz.

Each test case (not each Problem) must run in 1 second to receive credit. Exception: TestProblem3.test_08 must run in 5 seconds.

Instructions

This quiz assumes you have Python 3.6 (or a later version) installed on your machine.

This quiz is closed-book and closed-Internet -- you are only allowed to access the quiz page on the 6.009 website and the material provided in the .zip file. You are not allowed to access other information on your laptop or on the web. You may not discuss the quiz with other students, even after completion of the quiz, until regrades have been completed and final quiz grades assigned (at the end of next week), because many students will still be working on regrades or conflict offerings of the quiz. In the case of this practice quiz, however, you may discuss with other students as part of your preparation for the actual quiz.

In addition to the quiz.py and test.py files, you may also access the library.pdf file, which includes the chapters 1-4 of the Python Library Reference -- they cover the built-in functions (Chap. 2) and built-in data types (Chap. 4). Note that Python's built-in help function will provide a concise summary of built-in operations on data types (e.g., help(set)) or information about the arguments for the built-in functions (e.g., help(sorted)).

As in the labs, test.py can be used to test your code in quiz.py. Each of the problems has a suite of associated tests. You can run tests for a specific problem like so

python3 test.py problem1

or

pytest test.py -k problem1

This quiz is worth 20 points. Your quiz score will be based primarily on performance of your last code submitted during the quiz, tested against 20 test cases. However, points will also be lost in other circumstances:

  • You must not import any Python modules to use as part of your solutions -- quizzes with import statements (or their equivalent!) will be given grades of 0.

  • Having your code check for a specific input (called "hard coding") and then return a specific result is okay only for the base cases in iteration or recursion. Problem solutions that look for specific test case arguments other than base cases are disallowed and will receive no credit.

  • You do not have to include doctests or detailed comments in your code: we will not deduct any points for lack of comments, but encourage those as general good practice.

Aside from these special point deductions above, your quiz score will be based on the number of unittest tests your last submitted code passes. If you pass all of the tests, you'll receive full base credit. If you pass 15 of the 20 tests, you'll receive 75% of the base credit for the quiz (i.e., 15 points). Note also that to pass some of the tests in the time allotted, your solution may have to be reasonably efficient.

Problem 1. trailing_weighted_average(S, W)

The notion of a "trailing weighted average" is useful in several situations, e.g., for analyzing historical stock prices.

Write a function trailing_weighted_average(S, W) that computes the weighted moving average of a signal sequence S based on a weight sequence W. The signal S consists of a sequence of numbers of length m, while W is a sequence of numbers with length n where n is a non-negative integer. The value W[k] tells us how much to weight values from S that are k points in the "past", when computing the the averaged sequence A that is our output. Thus a weight W = [0.9, 0.2] tells us that A[22] will have value S[22]*0.9 + S[21]*0.2, and so on.

Mathematically, the operation will compute the sequence

A(i) = \sum_{k = 0}^{n-1} S(i-k) W(k)
for i = 0 to m-1 where m is the number of elements in S. Elements outside of the provided range of S should be assumed to be equal to the nearest-end values of S. Thus trailing_weighted_average([1, 2], [0.8, 0.7]) should return [1.5, 2.3]; the 1.5 value comes from 0.8 * 1 + 0.7 * 1, and the 2.3 value comes from 0.8 * 2 + 0.7 * 1. The output sequence A should be the same length as the input sequence S.

The original sequences S and W should not be modified.

Examples:

  • trailing_weighted_average([1, 2], [0.8, 0.7]) returns [1.5, 2.3]
  • trailing_weighted_average([1, 5, 6, 7], [1]) returns [1, 5, 6, 7]
  • trailing_weighted_average([1, 5, 6, 7], [0.5, 0.5]) returns [1.0, 3.0, 5.5, 6.5]
  • trailing_weighted_average([1, 5, 6, 7], [0, 1]) returns [1, 1, 5, 6]
  • trailing_weighted_average([1, 5, 6, 7], [1, 0]) returns [1, 5, 6, 7]
  • trailing_weighted_average([1, 5, 6, 7], [2, 0, 0, 0, 100]) returns [102, 110, 112, 114]

Problem 2. all_consecutives(vals, n)

Write a function all_consecutives(vals, n) that takes two arguments: vals is a set of integers, and n is an integer greater than 0. The function all_consecutives should return a set of all "consecutive sequences" of length n that can be constructed from the values in vals. The members of the return set must satisfy two requirements. First, each "consecutive sequence" in the output set must be a tuple where the elements of the tuple are consecutive integers. Thus (20, 21, 22) is a valid "consecutive sequence", while (20, 22) is not because 22 is not consecutive with 20. Second, all of the members of the tuple must also be members of the input set vals.

Examples:

  • all_consecutives({0, 1, 2, 3, 4}, 1) returns {(0,), (1,), (2,), (3,), (4,)}
  • all_consecutives({0, 1, 2, 3, 4}, 2) returns {(0, 1), (3, 4), (2, 3), (1, 2)}
  • all_consecutives({0, 1, 2, 3, 4}, 5) returns {(0, 1, 2, 3, 4)}
  • all_consecutives({0, 1, 2, 3, 4}, 6) returns set()
  • all_consecutives({0, 2, 4}, 1) returns {(2,), (0,), (4,)}
  • all_consecutives({0, 2, 4}, 2) returns set()
  • all_consecutives({0, 83, 2, 3, 81, 7, 82}, 2) returns {(81, 82), (2, 3), (82, 83)}

Problem 3. cost_to_consume(seq1, seq2)

Suppose we have two sequences, seq1 and seq2. We have a process that "consumes" the entirety of these two sequences by successively processing elements at the front of the two sequences, but with a very specific set of consumption rules; each rule comes with a corresponding cost. The possible consumption steps and costs are the following:

  • FREE: the first element in the two sequences are the same element; the two can be consumed together, with a cost of 0

  • BOTH: the first element in the two sequences are different; the two can be be consumed together, but with a cost of 1

  • SINGLE: only a single element -- either the element at the front of seq1, or the element at the front of seq2 -- can be consumed; this also has a cost of 1

Thus, there are multiple ways to complete the consumption of all of the elements in seq1 and seq2, and those ways may have different costs. For example, if seq1 is "ab" and seq2 is "b", we could consume BOTH 'a' and 'b' simultaneously from the front of these sequences with cost 1, then consume the remaining 'b' from seq2 with the SINGLE cost of 1, for a total cost to consume seq1 and seq2 of 2. Alternatively, we could consume just the SINGLE 'a' at the front of seq1 first (for a cost of 1); then consume the two matching 'b''s at zero cost, for a total cost to consume seq1 and seq2 of 1. Thus the minimum cost_to_consume(seq1, seq2) in this case is 1.

Write the function cost_to_consume(seq1, seq2) that takes two sequence arguments, and returns the minimum cost to fully consume these two sequences under the rules above.

Examples:

  • cost_to_consume('ab', 'b') returns 1
  • cost_to_consume('mast', 'mast') returns 0
  • cost_to_consume('mast', 'must') returns 1
  • cost_to_consume('misty', 'must') returns 2
  • cost_to_consume('color', 'colour') returns 1
  • cost_to_consume('car', 'boat') returns 3
  • cost_to_consume('frog', 'apple') returns 5
  • cost_to_consume('aba', 'bbb') returns 2
  • cost_to_consume('aba', 'bab') returns 2

Note that in order to pass some of the test cases, your code will need to be efficient enough to run to completion within the specified timeout.

Each test case (not each Problem) must run in 1 second to receive credit. Exception: TestProblem3.test_08 must run in 5 seconds.
